<document>
	<title>&quot;Fast isoamylases&quot; in the parotid saliva of children with cystic
   fibrosis and heterozygous carriers.</title>

	<author>Doering-K-M.</author>
	<author>Arglebe-C.</author>
	<author>Lubahn-H.</author>
	<author>Chilla-R.</author>

	<source>Eur-J-Pediatr. 1977 Oct 12. 126(3). P 185-8.</source>

	<abstract>On electrophoresis, parotid saliva always exhibits a basic pattern of
   6 isoamylases. Additional faster migrating isoamylases occur in
   varying numbers. These &quot;fast isoamylases&quot; are generated, at least in
   part, by deamidation. Compared with juvenile and adult controls, a
   significantly greater number of &quot;fast isoamylases&quot; was found in the
   parotid saliva of children with cystic fibrosis and their healthy
   heterozygous parents. A shift in the equilibrium between amidation
   and deamidation is discussed in terms of its possible connection with
   the metabolic defect responsible for cystic fibrosis.</abstract>

